7:["$","section",null,{"className":"faq-page-resource-strip","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"container","children":[["$","div",null,{"children":[["$","svg",null,{"aria-hidden":"true","className":"","fill":"none","viewBox":"0 0 24 24","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":"1.8","strokeLinecap":"round","strokeLinejoin":"round","children":[["$","path",null,{"d":"M12 22s8-4 8-11V5l-8-3-8 3v6c0 7 8 11 8 11Z"}],["$","path",null,{"d":"m9 12 2 2 4-4"}]]}],["$","p",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Planning note:"}]," Alberta micro-generation, municipal permitting, retailer credit terms and incentives can change. Confirm the current rules before relying on them for a project decision."]}]]}],["$","a",null,{"href":"/solar-incentives-financing","children":["Explore incentives & financing ",["$","svg",null,{"aria-hidden":"true","className":"","fill":"none","viewBox":"0 0 24 24","stroke":"currentColor","strokeWidth":"1.8","strokeLinecap":"round","strokeLinejoin":"round","children":[["$","path",null,{"d":"M5 12h14"}],["$","path",null,{"d":"m13 6 6 6-6 6"}]]}]]}]]}]}]
8:["$","section",null,{"className":"section faq-page-questions","id":"questions","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"container","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"faq-page-heading centered","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"kicker","children":"Search or browse"}],["$","h2",null,{"children":"Clear, practical solar answers."}],["$","p",null,{"children":"Choose a topic or search for a question. Each answer is written to help you prepare for a more useful solar assessment."}]]}],["$","$L10",null,{"categories":["Getting Started","Costs and Savings","Alberta Weather","Installation and Approvals","Micro-Generation and Electricity Bills","Commercial and Agricultural Solar","Maintenance and Ownership"],"faqs":[{"category":"Getting Started","question":"Is my home or property suitable for solar panels?","answer":"Possibly—many Alberta homes, businesses and rural properties can be considered, but suitability starts with a site review. Roof orientation, shading, structure, electrical service, available land and your actual electricity use all affect what can be designed responsibly. A proposal should also account for future roof work, access, utility requirements and how the property operates through the year."},{"category":"Getting Started","question":"How is the right solar-system size calculated?","answer":"The right size is based first on your electricity consumption, not on a generic panel count. We review bills, usage patterns, roof or land opportunities, equipment options and Alberta micro-generation requirements to identify a practical starting point. A system may also need to reflect planned changes such as electric heating, irrigation, equipment expansion or a future suite."},{"category":"Getting Started","question":"Why does Sun Direct Renewable need my electricity bills?","answer":"Your electricity bills show the consumption history that a solar design needs to address. They help identify seasonal use, meter information, delivery charges and the right questions to ask about on-site use and exported energy. Without that record, a system size or savings discussion can become too generic to be useful."},{"category":"Getting Started","question":"Should I replace my roof before installing solar panels?","answer":"If a roof is nearing the end of its useful life, coordinating roof work before solar is often worth considering. Removing and reinstalling panels later can add cost, scheduling and warranty coordination to a future roofing project. The roof condition, structure, drainage and anticipated roof timeline should be reviewed before final system design."},{"category":"Costs and Savings","question":"How much does a solar system cost in Alberta?","answer":"Solar system pricing varies because each property and design is different. Electricity usage, system size, roof or land conditions, equipment, permits, interconnection work and project complexity all affect the proposal. Financing, retailer export-credit arrangements and any applicable program requirements should be reviewed separately from the installed system price."},{"category":"Costs and Savings","question":"How much can solar reduce my electricity bill?","answer":"Solar can reduce the electricity you need to buy from the grid when your property uses power while the system is producing. The result depends on your usage, system size, utility rates, seasonal production and retailer credit arrangements for excess energy. Transmission, distribution, administration and other fixed charges may still appear on an Alberta electricity bill."},{"category":"Costs and Savings","question":"How long does it take for solar panels to pay for themselves?","answer":"There is no single payback period that applies to every Alberta solar project. It changes with electricity use, system cost, production, utility and retailer terms, financing, permits and future property needs. A useful proposal should show its assumptions clearly rather than promise a specific return date."},{"category":"Costs and Savings","question":"Are solar rebates, incentives, or financing available in Alberta?","answer":"Available options can include municipal property-based financing, retailer credit arrangements and business tax considerations, but they do not apply to every property. Alberta does not currently offer a universal provincial residential solar rebate. Current eligibility, application timing and financing terms must be confirmed with the official program, lender, retailer or tax professional before a decision is made."},{"category":"Alberta Weather","question":"Do solar panels work during Alberta winters?","answer":"Yes—solar panels continue producing electricity in cold weather when sunlight reaches the modules. Winter output can be lower because daylight hours are shorter, cloud cover can be heavier, the sun is lower and snow may cover the array. Annual production should be modeled using the property’s orientation, shading and local solar-resource assumptions rather than a seasonal promise."},{"category":"Alberta Weather","question":"What happens when snow covers the solar panels?","answer":"Snow coverage can temporarily reduce or stop production from the covered part of an array. How long it remains depends on snowfall, panel angle, temperature, wind, sun exposure and safe access to the roof or site. Any snow-management decision should prioritize safety and follow the equipment and installer guidance instead of risking damage or a fall."},{"category":"Alberta Weather","question":"Can solar panels withstand hail, wind, and extreme cold?","answer":"Solar equipment is selected and installed to meet applicable product, structural and electrical requirements for the project. Site conditions such as roof structure, wind exposure, mounting design and local permit requirements still need to be assessed individually. Cold itself does not prevent PV cells from producing, but the complete system design must account for Alberta weather, equipment ratings and safe installation."},{"category":"Installation and Approvals","question":"How long does the complete solar installation process take?","answer":"The complete process includes assessment, design, permitting, utility review, equipment scheduling, installation, inspection and activation. Timing changes with property complexity, municipal and utility requirements, roof or land conditions, material availability and season. A project schedule should identify its own approvals and dependencies instead of relying on a universal timeline."},{"category":"Installation and Approvals","question":"What happens during a solar site survey?","answer":"A site survey checks the practical conditions behind a proposal, including roof or land area, shading, electrical equipment, access and safety considerations. For businesses and farms, it can also include operating loads, meter arrangements, equipment schedules and future expansion plans. The survey helps turn preliminary electricity data into a design that can be reviewed for permits and utility interconnection."},{"category":"Installation and Approvals","question":"Who handles permits, utility applications, and inspections?","answer":"Sun Direct Renewable can coordinate the project information and installation process, while permits, utility applications and inspections follow the responsible authority’s requirements. In Calgary, photovoltaic work requires applicable electrical permitting and qualified installation, and other permits can be needed depending on the site. Utility approval and inspection outcomes remain with the relevant authorities and cannot be guaranteed in advance."},{"category":"Installation and Approvals","question":"When can my solar system be activated?","answer":"Activation follows completion of the required installation work, inspections, utility interconnection steps and meter or retailer arrangements where applicable. A grid-connected system should not be treated as ready simply because panels are installed. The final activation sequence depends on the property’s utility service provider, approved design and completion of the required documentation."},{"category":"Micro-Generation and Electricity Bills","question":"What happens to excess electricity produced by my system?","answer":"Solar electricity is used by the property first when there is on-site demand. Excess electricity may be exported to the grid and credited through your electricity retailer under the applicable micro-generation and retailer arrangements. Retailer credit rates and terms vary, and utility approval plus an interconnection agreement are required for a grid-connected micro-generation system."},{"category":"Micro-Generation and Electricity Bills","question":"Will I still receive an electricity bill after going solar?","answer":"Yes, most grid-connected solar customers continue to receive an electricity bill. Solar can reduce grid electricity consumption and exported electricity may create retailer credits, but transmission, distribution, administration, local access and other charges can remain. Your bill will also reflect periods when the property needs electricity from the grid, such as at night or when production is lower."},{"category":"Micro-Generation and Electricity Bills","question":"What happens during a power outage?","answer":"Most standard grid-connected solar systems shut down during a power outage to protect utility workers and the electrical system. Solar panels alone do not keep household or business circuits running when the grid is down. Backup operation requires compatible battery storage and properly designed backup equipment, which should be discussed as a separate resilience feature."},{"category":"Commercial and Agricultural Solar","question":"Can farms and agricultural properties benefit from solar?","answer":"They can, especially where barns, workshops, grain handling, irrigation, ventilation, refrigeration or cold storage create meaningful daytime loads. Farm projects require their own review of meter configuration, service capacity, seasonal operations, roof or land suitability and municipal or land-classification considerations. Farms should not assume that a grant, tax treatment or export arrangement applies without confirming the current rules for the entity and property."},{"category":"Commercial and Agricultural Solar","question":"Is solar suitable for commercial buildings and high-energy-use businesses?","answer":"Solar can be considered for commercial rooftops, facilities and high-use operations where the site, loads and interconnection path are suitable. A commercial assessment should review electricity consumption, demand patterns, roof condition, operating schedules, access and ownership requirements. Financing and federal tax considerations may be relevant for qualifying organizations, but each must be confirmed separately with the appropriate professional or program."},{"category":"Maintenance and Ownership","question":"What maintenance does a solar system need after installation?","answer":"Solar systems are generally designed for routine operation with monitoring, visual checks and an understanding of the equipment handover. The property owner should know how to review alerts, keep access areas safe and arrange qualified support if damage, electrical issues or unusual performance is suspected. Site-specific responsibilities can also include vegetation control for ground mounts and coordination with future roof work."},{"category":"Maintenance and Ownership","question":"Who owns and supports the system after installation?","answer":"Ownership and support arrangements depend on the purchase, financing or property-based financing structure chosen for the project. Your agreement should clearly identify equipment ownership, monitoring access, workmanship commitments, product documentation and the steps to take if the property changes hands. Keep project records, permits, utility documents and system information with the property for future service or sale discussions."}]}]]}]}]
